1. Leadership Model

Multiple team leaders can exist simultaneously
No single “global admin”

Leadership is:

Scoped (per team)
Explicitly granted
Revocable

2. Inter-Team Coordination

Teams are independent by default

Teams may:

Establish explicit trust relationships with other teams
Share only specific tasks / datasets
Do so temporarily or persistently
No automatic data visibility across teams

Think:

“Joint task force, not merged organizations.”

3. Data Model: Decentralized + Zero Trust (Hard Requirement)
What “Zero Trust” Means Here

No device is trusted by default
No leader is trusted globally
No team is trusted implicitly

Every action requires:

Authentication
Authorization
Cryptographic proof

Data Characteristics

Data is:

Locally stored
Encrypted at rest
Encrypted in transit

No central server holding team state
No global database

4. Practical Architecture (This Is Important)

This cannot be a traditional client-server app.
What you’re describing maps best to:

🔐 A Federated, Peer-to-Peer Trust Graph

Core concepts:

Identity
Device-bound cryptographic identity
Keypair generated locally
Team
Logical container
Defined by a set of trusted identities + permissions

Leader

A role, not a god-mode account

Granted via cryptographic capability

Task

Shareable object

Can be selectively exposed across trust boundaries

5. Example Flow (Concrete)
Adding a Member

Member generates local identity

Leader approves via:

QR code
Out-of-band key exchange
Leader issues capabilities, not raw access

Member receives:

Only team data they are authorized for
Inter-Team Task Sharing

Team A creates Task X

Team A selects:

Which team(s) to share with
What fields are visible
Duration of access

Team B receives:

A cryptographically signed task reference
No access to Team A’s broader data
Access expires or is revoked cleanly

6. What This Forbids (Explicitly)

To keep zero-trust honest, these are NOT allowed:

❌ Global admin dashboards
❌ Central identity provider you control
❌ “Convenience” cloud sync by default
❌ Silent metadata sharing
❌ Auto-discovery of teams or users

Everything is:

Opt-in
Explicit
Verifiable

7. Engineering Consequences (Good + Hard)
Pros

Extremely strong privacy guarantees
Real community trust
Hard to compromise at scale
Legally safer (no data custody)

Costs

More complex sync logic
More explicit UX steps
Key management UX matters a lot
Revocation must be designed carefully

This is not a beginner system — but it is a defensible one.

